\begin{abstract}
The performance of novel two-dimensional nitrides in carbon capture and storage (CCS) is analyzed for a broad range of pressure and temperature conditions. Employing an integrated theoretical framework where $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ adsorption/desorption rates on the $\mathrm{M}_{2} \mathrm{~N}(\mathrm{M}=\mathrm{Ti}, \mathrm{Zr}, \mathrm{Hf}, \mathrm{V}, \mathrm{Nb}, \mathrm{Ta}, \mathrm{Cr}, \mathrm{Mo}, \mathrm{W})$ surface are derived from transition state theory and density functional theory based calculations, the present theoretical simulations consistently predict that, depending on the particular composition, $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ can be strongly adsorbed and even activated at temperatures above $1000 \mathrm{~K}$. For practical purposes, $\mathrm{Ti}_{2} \mathrm{~N}, \mathrm{Zr}_{2} \mathrm{~N}, \mathrm{Hf}_{2} \mathrm{~N}, \mathrm{~V}_{2} \mathrm{~N}$, $\mathrm{Nb}_{2} \mathrm{~N}, \mathrm{Ta}_{2} \mathrm{~N}$ are predicted as the best suited materials for $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ activation. Moreover, the estimated $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ uptake of $2.32-7.96 \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{CO}_{2} \cdot \mathrm{kg}^{-1}$ reinforces the potential of these materials for $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ abatement.
\end{abstract}

